#compdef myurls
# ============================================================================
# myurls - your own URL shortener (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Carey Wang (CareyWang)
# Upstream: https://github.com/CareyWang/MyUrls
#
# `myurls` is a self-hosted URL shortener that maps
# short-code paths to redirect-target URLs via a
# Redis-backed key/value store. The HTTP server
# exposes:
#   POST /short          - create a new short URL
#   GET  /<short-code>   - 302-redirect to the
#                           stored target URL
#   GET  /              - serve the bundled
#                           static-asset homepage
#                           (frontend SPA)
#
# Architecture:
#   - Gin HTTP server for the REST API
#   - go-redis/v9 client for state persistence
#   - In-process 1GB ballast to reduce GC churn
#     under high request rates
#
# Use case: drop-in replacement for goo.gl /
# bit.ly / TinyURL when you want the shortener
# infrastructure on your own domain + your own
# Redis instance for the persistent state.
#
# Usage:
#   myurls [flags]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag.* parsing):
#   --port <port>         - HTTP server port
#                            (default 8080)
#   --domain <domain>     - public domain (used in
#                            generated short URLs)
#                            (default localhost:8080)
#   --proto <proto>       - public protocol
#                            (default https)
#   --conn <addr:port>    - Redis address
#                            (default
#                            localhost:6379)
#   --password <pw>       - Redis AUTH password
#                            (default empty)
#   -h                    - print help
#
# Environment overrides (env vars take precedence
# over CLI flags):
#   MYURLS_PORT
#   MYURLS_DOMAIN
#   MYURLS_PROTO
#   MYURLS_CONN
#   MYURLS_PASSWORD
#
# The go-redis lane is built on `github.com/redis/
# go-redis/v9 v9.8.0` (declared verbatim at upstream
# go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, imported as `"github.
# com/redis/go-redis/v9"` then `redis.Options{Addr,
# Password, DB}` + `rc.Ping(ctx)` + `rc.Set/Get`),
# the canonical Go Redis client by Vladimir
# Mihailenco - github.com/redis/go-redis, 22000+
# stars.
#
# go-redis has an interesting governance history:
#   1. Mihailenco started the library in 2014 at
#      github.com/go-redis/redis as `go-redis/redis`
#      - the de-facto Go Redis client since the
#      earliest days of the Go ecosystem
#   2. 2017: gained Pipeline + Cluster + Sentinel +
#      pub/sub support; reached canonical-Go-Redis
#      status displacing earlier alternatives
#      (gosexy/redis, gomodule/redigo)
#   3. v8 (2020): added context.Context-aware APIs
#      across the whole command surface
#   4. v9 (2023): RESP3 protocol support + Redis 7
#      streams + cluster-redirect improvements
#   5. 2023: REPO TRANSITIONED from go-redis/redis
#      to redis/go-redis under Redis Inc.'s official
#      `redis` GitHub org. The import path remains
#      `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` (the Go module
#      path follows the new repo location). The
#      transition formally blessed Mihailenco's
#      client as Redis Inc.'s canonical Go client,
#      similar to:
#      - NodeRedis/node-redis at Axis 255's Node
#        slot (also under Redis Inc.'s org)
#      - redis/redis-py at the Python ecosystem's
#        equivalent
#
# This corporate-canonical-blessing pattern is unique
# to the Go + Node + Python slots in the Redis
# ecosystem. Compare:
#   - Rust (Axis 255 slot 1): mitsuhiko/redis-rs
#     stays under Ronacher's personal canonical
#     position; Redis Inc. has not formally blessed a
#     Rust client (the redis-rs/redis-rs org acts as
#     the community canonical)
#   - Go (Axis 255 slot 2, THIS FILE): redis/go-redis
#     formally blessed under Redis Inc.
#   - Node (Axis 255 closing): NodeRedis/node-redis
#     under Redis Inc.
#   - Python (off-axis): redis-py under Redis Inc.
#
# Mihailenco continues as primary maintainer post-
# transition, but the org move signals the long-term
# commitment from Redis Inc. to the client
# ecosystem.
#
# myurls uses go-redis for:
#   - `rc.Ping(ctx)` on startup as a Redis-health
#     check
#   - `rc.Set(ctx, code, target, 0)` for new short
#     URL creation
#   - `rc.Get(ctx, code)` for redirect resolution
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 255 :: Redis protocol (RESP) client libraries
# Round 1464 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 255
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : mitsuhiko/redis-rs           [R1463 _ocypod-server]
#             (community canonical, not
#              Redis Inc.-blessed)
#   Go      : redis/go-redis (Vladimir     [R1464 THIS FILE]
#             Mihailenco; Redis Inc.-
#             blessed since 2023)
#   TS/Node : NodeRedis/node-redis         [R1465 closing]
#             (Redis Inc.-blessed)
#
# redis/go-redis is structurally interesting in this
# axis because of the *org-transition-to-corporate-
# canonical* pattern in 2023. Vladimir Mihailenco's
# original work (go-redis/redis since 2014) reached
# canonical-Go-Redis status through community
# adoption alone for ~9 years before Redis Inc.
# formally blessed the library by moving it under
# the `redis/` GitHub org alongside redis-py and
# node-redis.
#
# This pattern of *delayed-corporate-canonical-
# blessing* contrasts with:
#   - Rust (redis-rs): no Redis Inc. blessing;
#     stays community-canonical under Ronacher's
#     personal maintenance
#   - libraries with day-1 corporate provenance
#     (e.g. AWS SDK libraries, Google Cloud SDKs)
#     that are corporate-canonical from inception
#
# The transition matters operationally because
# Redis Inc. now coordinates the client library
# release cycle with Redis server feature
# announcements (vector search, JSON datatype,
# streams) - the v9 series tracks Redis 7+ features
# more aggressively than community-maintained
# alternatives would.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# RESP2 / RESP3 command stream produced by redis-rs +
# go-redis + node-redis is byte-identical to the
# Redis server's expected wire format.
# ============================================================================

_myurls() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--port[HTTP server port (default 8080)]:port:' \
        '--domain[public domain for generated short URLs]:domain:' \
        '--proto[public protocol]:proto:(http https)' \
        '--conn[Redis address]:addr:' \
        '--password[Redis AUTH password]:password:' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]'
}

_myurls "$@"
